ce:section.ce:para:
Different pore size distribution, functional groups, and excess unsaturated metal sites mainly lead to differences in adsorption capacity and consequently selectivity of adsorbents. According to the literature [69–71], at low pressure, the micropore volume and unsaturated metal sites are the main factors responsible for gas adsorption when monolayer uptake is performed. Moreover, since multilayer uptake is the predominant mechanism at high pressures, the mesopore volume plays a major role in high-pressure adsorption [72,73]. From the selectivity data (
                           Table S7
                        ), it can be inferred that based on the final application of the adsorbents, their surface properties can be tuning by changing the RC content, thereby adjusted the selectivity. The RC-ML-1 had the highest adsorption capacity toward all gases by having the highest micropore volume, optimal micropore/mesopore volume ratio, and creating access channels to more micropores. On the other hand, the presence of nitrogen-containing functional groups in RC led to improved electron distribution, increased surface energy, and facilitated surface interaction with CH4 and N2 gas molecules. Therefore, their adsorption capacity increased notably compared to H2S and CO2, which led to the worst selectivity. The lowest micropore/mesopore volume ratio in RC-ML-10 led to the best selectivity in the CO2 removal from CH4 and N2 mixtures. However, RC-ML-5, with a micropore/mesopore volume ratio of 1.43, had the best selectivity toward H2S. Since the pore filling is the main mechanism for CH4 and N2 gas uptake, increasing the average pore diameter greatly reduced their adsorption. In contrast, H2S and CO2 adsorption exhibit a relatively smaller decrease, owing to their high polarizability and strong interaction with functional groups and mesopore walls. Therefore, the preferred H2S and CO2 adsorption increased as the mesoporosity in MOF composite samples increased significantly. Moreover, it was found that the prepared adsorbents had the best selectivity in H2S/N2 and H2S/CH4 mixtures, respectively, attributed to the strong interaction between H2S with free metal sites of Cr ions and its ability to form hydrogen bonds with functional groups in the MOF crystals.
